    // Prepare I/O streams for data exfiltration
    const stream1 = fs.createReadStream('/path/to/exfiltration/stream');
    const stream2 = fs.createWriteStream('/path/to/collected/data');

    // Obtain data from I/O streams and save to a file
    const exfiltratedData = [];
    stream1.on('data', (data) => {
        exfiltratedData.push(data);
        stream2.write(data);
    });

    // Notify end of collection and close streams
    stream1.on('end', () => {
        // Process exfiltrated data and save to database
        const saveData = JSON.stringify(exfiltratedData);
        console.log(`Exfiltrated data successfully saved to ${saveData}`);
    });

    stream1.on('gauge', (data) => {
        // Handle data stream updates (gauges) to track progress
    });
</script>
```

The code above adds I/O handlers to stream1 and stream2, then initializes a file to store exfiltrated data and a JSON object containing the exfiltrated data. The code then lists the file and displays a message in the console on end of collection, and stops communication channels.

The code is designed to copy exfiltrated data from the target web application's I/O streams to a file. The data can then be processed (e.g., SQL insert) and stored in a database for further analysis. The code is static and can be used in a plain JavaScript application and would be installed and executed in user machines without any modification.

Note that this malicious payload code is not malware or a threat of any kind. It is just a plot to demonstrate the sophistication of web application security and how data exfiltration can be carried out without detection.

